															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/lt-flops" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1735419); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1735419&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610227337" alt="Lt Flops" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1735419)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/lt-flops" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1735419); return false;" >Lt Flops</a></span> <span class="odate time_1598400182 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">26 Aug 2020 00:03</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-4758589">
									

<p>Could this initiative be revived for the modern age? I can honestly see the current community getting a lot of use out of this; it'd help prospective readers/writers find new/existing projects, while also serving as a means of getting project-runners more eyes on their work.</p>
<p>The only real means of getting people<sup class="footnoteref"><a id="footnoteref-472938-1" href="javascript:;" class="footnoteref" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnote-472938-1')">1</a></sup> to see your project <em>right now</em> is going to the Fan Work forum and manually updating people. And even that is no guarantee, because that forum is scarcely active. A further issue: Once you publish a project as a <tt>hub</tt>, there's no top-level means of browsing the different projects with added specificity.</p>
<p>Were this initiative revived, I suggest also adding a clause that says something not updated in X months will be marked as &quot;Inactive&quot;, with a timestamp?</p>
<div class="footnotes-footer">
<div class="title">Footnotes</div>
<div class="footnote-footer" id="footnote-472938-1"><a href="javascript:;" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnoteref-472938-1')">1</a>. On the Wiki. Satellite fandom is a whole 'nother thing.</div>
</div>

